column2:
@sudotechie sort of right

you can join a lot of web3 communities without being an owner, though becoming an owner is definitely core to the model

in web3, in theory, you should also be able to show up and contribute without being an owner, and get compensated with ownership

@mviktoro i agree that not every little thing should be monetized

but I also think there's a point where someone is contributing enough that they deserve comp/upside

also there are people who don't have the ability to commit time/resources to open source projects without comp

@jill_rowley I've long been a big fan of the idea of an MVC.

Shout out to @danyacg for this one back in 2014 üëá

https://t.co/MKIVmUJscD

@M_M_martinelli @evanhamilton not sure I understand how PMF allows for that in a way that NPS doesn't?

I think both of them are pretty vague, which comes with the territory of being a singular metric

we always as lots of other questions around NPS to get a feel for why they choose that score

@evanhamilton ohhh i like that @iambethmcintyre what do you think?

we do use NPS pretty consistently across all our channels - it's good to have a benchmark to compare against and notice if it's going down

i think both could be effective in that regard

@Jihoz_Axie @cdixon Love this!

It's also important to note that the members who are part of production aren't necessarily the same members who are part of distribution.

Just like in web2, employees, advocates, and customers are all part of the "community" but in very different ways.

@jasongriffing @adamjacksonsf its an issue if the intention is to use tokens as compensation

if it's not used as compensation, and it only has reputational value, that's okay (and how online communities have always worked)

it just doesn't solve the compensation problem in that case
